# hilavitkutin-linking backlog

Type-surface reminder: every pub signature in this crate uses notko's fallibility ladder (Just / Maybe / Outcome), arvo primitives for numeric and boolean values, and fixed-capacity structured errors with no heap payloads. Path and symbol-name inputs are raw null-terminated byte slices at the FFI boundary. Collections do not cross the public API. The crate returns typed symbol handles, not containers of them.

## Designed, deferred

### Hot-reload ref-counting unload

v1 ships RAII unload plus an explicit `Library::close` that returns load-status. Both unload the library once. A future evolution may add ref-counted unload to support hot-reload scenarios where a consumer wants to reload the same library path while old handles may still exist. The current API rejects that use pattern by construction; the lifetime system prevents outstanding symbols from outliving their loader. Hot-reload needs a different contract (likely a versioned handle token) and that redesign is out of v1 scope.

### Async loading wrappers

v1 is synchronous. Loading a library blocks the calling thread for the duration of the OS dlopen call. A future evolution may layer async wrappers on top for hosts that want non-blocking load. The sync core stays; the async layer is purely additive.

### Wasm dlopen

The wasm32 targets do not expose a dlopen equivalent at the ABI level; wasm-component-model is a different mechanism entirely. Extending this crate to wasm32 is out of scope. If hilavitkutin-extensions needs wasm support, it lands via a separate transport.

### Library-level signing and signature verification

The loader trusts whatever the OS loader trusts. Signed-library enforcement, hash verification, or provenance policy is not handled here. Consumer-side policy layers that need these checks apply them before or after calling into this crate.

### Loader telemetry hooks

Hooks for load-time, resolution-time, and close-time callbacks (for observability wiring in downstream hosts) are out of v1 scope. The synchronous API makes these trivial to add externally without crate-level hooks; a future evolution may add them for symmetry.

### UTF-16 / wide-path support on Windows

v1 accepts ASCII-only paths on Windows (converted internally to UTF-16). Full UTF-8 to UTF-16 conversion for arbitrary path content lands in a future iteration; callers with ASCII-only paths are unaffected.

### Extended arities for `LibrarySymbol`

v1 admits `extern "C"` function pointer shapes at arities zero through eight. Higher arities are realistic only for niche ABIs; if a downstream consumer genuinely needs them, a new round widens the sealed trait coverage.
